Bumpkin Tales Part 9 - The Fires of Qeynos  
<br />
 
<br />
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
<br />
 12.01.00:0920  
<br />
 
<br />
 
<br />
 The storm clouds gathered over the small ruin on the shore of the lake. Rain started to pelt the remaining sections of the roof and walls of the small structure. A small fire lit the inside of the ruin. Seated by the fire was a small figure, bruised and battered, clinging to an oddly shaped sword, weeping softly. 
<br />

<br />
The rain pelted Ogark's pointy green ears. He walked towards his small house gleefully. He had had a good hunt, and was going to eat well for weeks on the food he had killed. Reaching the door, he paused shortly. His keen ears picked up the sound of weeping, as he smelt the burning odor of burning wood. He had not left his fire going when he went out. With a snarl, he burst through the door, planning on ripping out the intruder's thought. 
<br />

<br />
Dumbly rose from his seated position and swung his giant sword. With a gurgling growl, Ogark fell, his body cleaved in half by Dumbly's sword. "Hottil! You shall feel the sting of the Bumpkin sword next!" He slowly packed up his small camp, and looked at the sky through a hole in the roof. The rain would continue for hours, better for him to just walk, he would waste too much time waiting for the rain to stop. He slung his sword over his shoulder, and began his journey. He was going to find, and kill Hottil. 
<br />

<br />
Didley woke up in a cold sweat; he had just had the worst nightmare of his life. In his morbid dream, he saw the corpses of warriors long fallen rise up and attack his new home, Qeynos. He quickly got up and put his robe on, and ran to the window. People were running through the streets, and the guard was calling for all defenders of Qeynos to come to the gate and defend their fine city. Didley quickly put on his armor, grabbed his mace and his shield, said a prayer to Brell and ran to the gate. By the time Didley had gotten to the gate, most of the defenders had fallen to the mass of gnolls and undead. Shouting prayers to Brell, Didley struck down all that came his way. He was very aware that they were loosing, and loosing bad. The defenders had lost nearly a third of their numbers, and the legions of darkness seemed endless. 
<br />

<br />
"To the clock tower, to make our final stand!" shouted the head of the guard as he attempted to rally the troops. 
<br />

<br />
A large mass of undead and gnolls followed and cut down the attackers as they retreated. Didley was dealt a stunning blow by a grinning corpse. He fell to the ground and quickly rolled into a back ally to avoid being trampled by the horde of evil following him. He began walking down the ally towards the clock tower when he heard a soft thump behind him. As he turned he swung his mace at the source of the noise, suddenly, he felt cold steel pierce his chest. He coughed and looked in surprise at the amount of blood that he had just expelled into his hand. He attempted one final healing prayer, the words spilling out of his dying mouth. As he began to say the final word, he felt a cold sharp object enter his neck, and he knew no more. 
<br />

<br />
Hottil wiped the blade of his knife off as Didley's corpse slid to the ground. Two Bumpkins down, two to go he thought to himself as he hurried into the sewer to continue his search for Dudley. 
<br />

<br />
Dudley, his lungs burning, paused his headlong run at the top of a high hill. Dead ahead of him lay the city of Qeynos. Once a beautiful city, it now glowed in the night gloom like some evil demon, most of the eastern half of the city in flames. Apparently, the city had shipped some wizards from Odus, and they had dealt with most of the invaders, setting fire to a good portion of the city in the process. Dudley knew he would find his brother in the battle, smiting the undead or healing the wounded. He unsheathed his sword and, screaming his battle cry, ran towards the city.  
<br />

<br />
 
<br />

<br />
Bumpkin Tales Part 10  
<br />
 
<br />
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
<br />
 01.22.01:0815  
<br />
 
<br />
 
<br />
 Dudley ran as he had never run before. His enemy was in he city, as was his brother. There was no choice Dudley had to kill Hottil. The rational part of Dudley’s mind had departed, leaving only his battle rage. Dudley’s eyes were a glazed red color, his vision blurred with the mist of blood fury. He unstraped his sword and redid it in his hands as he neared the fallen gates of Qyenos. A skeleton stood in his way, its bony fingers dripping blood from the man it had just killed, hearing Dudley’s shout, it turned around. Dudley paid it no mind as he absentmindedly swung his sword, not slowing his frantic run. The skeleton disintegrated from the powerful blow of Dudley’s sword. Dudley ran on. 
<br />

<br />
Hottil, realizing that the battle was swinging in the defender’s favor, decided that it was time to run. Hearing the screams and sounds of battle, he headed the opposite way, hoping to find a way out of the city. He ran down side allies and streets, attempting to avoid any fighting. He sighed as he reached the courtyard in front of the gate, and was relieved to see only a small child blocking his way out of the city. 
<br />

<br />
Dudley, not knowing where the battle was taking place, had slowed after entering the gate, trying to find the quickest route to the fighting. He heard footsteps, and prepared himself for battle. He did not expect the figure running towards him to be Hottil. 
<br />

<br />
Hottil ran straight at the figure, hoping to knock it over and escape, but he did not expect the figure to be Dudley. Running full tilt, and realizing whom he was running towards too late, Hottil smashed into Dudley’s chest plate, knocking the wind out of both halflings. With a scream filled with hate and rage, Dudley swung his giant sword, aiming for Hottil’s head. Hottil lightly stepped to the side, slashing Dudley across his stomach through an opening in his armor. Dudley screamed in rage, not noticing the cut, and continued to hack away at Hottil. Hottil held his dagger up in a pathetic attempt to parry Dudley’s frenzied swings. Hottil’s only hope was to distract the enraged warrior long enough to escape through the sewer. Hottil had to think quickly, his arm beginning to numb from Dudley’s frenzied swings. 
<br />

<br />
Dudley was excited; he finally had Hottil at his mercy, and was going to savor every moment of the Halfling thief’s pain. He swung and swung, content to beat at Hottil until his small dagger broke and Dudley could finish him off. Hottil, his dagger finally breaking, held up something in his other hand. Dudley paused as he began to swing to see what it was. It was Didley’s squad ring; a ring given out by the wall guard to signify that the person wearing it was an honorary member. Didley had been trying to earn his when Dudley had last seen him. If Didley had gotten the ring, then he would never had relinquished it to Hottil unless Hottil had killed him. Dudley roared and brought his sword down upon the prone form of Hottil, but his momentary laps of concentration had cost him dearly as Hottil’s boot connected squarely with his jaw, knocking the halfling warrior onto his back. Hottil then, tossing the ring to Dudley, Hit Dudley in the head until the Halfling warrior stopped moving, and ran off. Dudley woke later, with a massive headache, and the knowledge that another of his kin had fallen to the viscous blade of Hottil. 
<br />

<br />
Dumbly made his way across the ruins of yet another lizard city. The young halfling warrior knew that he had to get to the Elvin outpost at Firiona Vie and get back to the mainland so he could continue his hunt for Hottil. 
<br />

<br />
Clairion was a young elf by eleven standards, yet he was already a seasoned adventurer, and a rather well known ranger. He had ventured to Kunark in hopes of finding some sorts of fame or fortune so he could return to Kelethin a hero, and wed Nightrose, his beloved. He carried a golden locket with a painting of her beautiful face around his neck, and he sang songs about the glory that he would bring her as he walked. He was not as naive as he seemed however, his beautiful, almond shaped eyes were always looking left and right, never missing a detail, and he listened to all that nature had to tell him. He had been hunting goblins around a lake that seemed to once have been a mighty city when he caught sight of a young halfling in need. He drew his twin blades and prepared for a hearty battle. 
<br />

<br />
Dumbly recognized the goblins too late, as they brutally attacked him, calling the name of their dead kinsman that Dumbly had killed. Dumbly easily parried their clumsily thrusts with their crude and dull weapons, easily killing one of the stupid clumsy creatures. He began to worry as two more goblins approached, one wearing the feathers and war paint of a shaman of some sorts. Dumbly knew that if he could not get to the shaman before he began to cast, that Dumbly was done for. He dispatched another goblin with a downward thrust that broke its crude sword and nearly cut the goblin’s head in half. The other goblin was a bit more cautious than the other two, and circled around Dumbly, cackling evenly as the shaman began to chant a spell. Holding his sword in a defensive position Dumbly suddenly produced a dagger in one of his hands and flung it at the chanting shaman. It hit the goblin in the arm, and momentarily destroyed its concentration. It pulled the dagger out and licked it, as it began the spell again. The other goblin, noticing Dumbly’s attention turning towards the shaman, chose this time to attack. He feigned a slice low, and came at the prone halfling high. His swing went wide, and with a gurgle the goblin pitched foreword with a barbed shaft in its back. The shaman, noticing the attack, lost concentration again, but the spell was too far along to simply stop. The poison cloud that the shaman had originally meant to direct at Dumbly appeared above the shaman’s head. Screaming, the shaman ran violent around in circles until the poison had eaten his flesh from his bones, and with a gurgle, the puddle fell to the ground. 
<br />

<br />
“Tis a shame,” a singsong voice stated, “To waste such a good arrow on this filth.” Clairion stepped out of he shadows and bowed to Dumbly, his long hair flowing over his head like a golden shower. “My name is Clairion, I am a ranger of Tunare and friend to the good. I should hope that we are on the same side, for to get back to the Eleven outpost is quite a trek, and dangerous fiends would be better fought by two then one.” 
<br />

<br />
“Me Dumbly.” Stated Dumbly happily, “Dumbly would love your help, Dumbly lost and he needs to get back to the mainland to help his brothers.” 
<br />

<br />
“Good then Dumbly, shall we be going, the rest of the goblin tribe will be missing their scouting party, and they will be too much for even you and I to take.” 
<br />

<br />
Without a word, Dumbly got up, and started walking towards a river, that they both assumed lead to the ocean. 
<br />

<br />
Hottil was elated. Not only had he killed Didley, but he had bested Dudley. He did not want to kill the halfling because he wanted to best him in equal combat; he wanted to win his pride back. His infravisoin giving him some sort of guidance, he traveled through the tunnels and catacombs of Qynos, trying to find an exit, so he could travel to guk, where he would obtain a guise of the deceiver that would allow him to walk among the Dark Elves, and hone his fighting skills to a new edge. Seeing light, he headed towards it and was suppressed to find it leading to a small chamber, not outside. He heard a slick shuffling noise and groaned when he realized where he had ended up, as the zombie began to attack.
<br />
 
<br />

<br />
 
<br />

<br />
Bumpkin Tales Part 11  
<br />
 
<br />
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
<br />
 01.22.01:0822  
<br />
 
<br />
 
<br />

<br />
 Dumbly genuinely enjoyed the time he spent with Clairion. The good-hearted ranger was a pleasant companion, and invaluable in a fight. Dumbly and Clairion reached the stream that fed the lake in no time, and Clairion estimated that the stream would lead them to the ocean, where they would find the outpost. 
<br />

<br />
“So as I was saying,” Clairion said, “I think that we should just follow this river and then we follow the ocean shore. It shouldn’t be more than half a days march to Friona Vie.” 
<br />

<br />
As the pair walked they started to hear some odd sounds. They looked around, but could not find the creatures making them. “Keep on your toes Dumbly.” Clairion warned, “Something is not right here.” 
<br />

<br />
As Clairion talked, Dumbly watched a small creature struggle against feet that no longer seemed to work. The small creature was covered with exquisite silver plate, probably mitheral Dumbly thought, and was armed with a large hammer and a shield with a picture of Brell Serilios on it. Dumbly recognized the picture as his god, and immediately unslung his sword and ran towards the figure. As Dumbly neared the struggling creature, he began to recognize its race. It was about Dumbly’s height, but had a large helmet, with horns on its head. Under the helmet, Dumbly could see a long read beard flowing down to its chest and a large nose poking out from its face. “Oh.” Said Clairion, “Dumbly! Don’t get to close, something rooted that Cleric. Wait for me!” With that, Clairion drew his two swords and charged towards the dwarf. 
<br />

<br />
As they ran, the dwarf’s tormentor showed itself. It resembled a dark elf, but where it should have had legs, it had a bulbous spider body with eight legs. When it moved, it made the sound that Dumbly and Clairion had been hearing the whole day. It paused, sizing up the new threat, and began to chant a spell. 
<br />

<br />
Knowing that it was about to cast a spell, Clairion reached to his druidic powers and cast a small stunning spell. It did no real damage, but it stopped the drachnid’s casting long enough for Dumbly to reach it. The halfling had not had a chance to use the sword to its fullest extent yet, but this battle promised to change that. Dumbly attacked with a reckless abandon, his giant sword sweeping and slashing faster than seemed possible. Clairion had to admit that it was impressive to see Dumbly wielding the sword so effectively when it was as big as the halfling. Dumbly’s slashes were doing some minor damage, but the drachnid’s tough shell was causing him some problems. He was having trouble cutting through the armor. He continued to chop away, assuming that sooner or later he would weaken the creature and be able to hit its soft upper torso. 
<br />

<br />
Clairion felt that while Dumbly handled the Drachnid and prevented it from casting, that he could try and free the dwarf. He examined the dwarf’s legs and found them magically rooted to the ground. 
<br />

<br />
“If ye gives me a sec I can free meself.” The Dwarf said. His face straining, trying to remember the prayer. His face flashed with joy when he finally remembered it, and with a quick murmur, he was free. He hoisted his hammer and started swinging it in circles above his head, shouting prayers to Brell as he charged. 
<br />

<br />
Dumbly was still hacking away at the tough chitin of the drachnid, determined to get through the armor of his larger opponent. The Drachnid was swinging wildly with its arms, trying to catch the young halfling, but Dumbly was too quick. Both the combatants were surprised when Dumbly’s sword finally cut into the drachnid’s belly. But the sword didn’t just cut; it burst into flames, covering the drachnid in a cloud of fire. The spider thing schreaked and flailed wildly, but the stinging hot sword once again entered the wound and ignited more flames inside the drachnid. The spider fiend started to run, but was felled when the dwarven cleric’s hammer smashed in its head. The Dwarf picked up his hammer and turned to Clairion. 
<br />

<br />
“Me thanks you have for saving me life.” He said, “Me name is Stonesplif Bligdenstone, and I be headed to Firiona Vie, to get off of this accursed isle, if ye are going the same way, mayhap we can walk together, there be many dangerous beasties about.” 
<br />

<br />
Clarion introduced Dumbly and himself, and the three headed off, flowing the river to the sea, hoping to find Firiona Vie.<br />_________________<br />Dumbly Bumpkin
<br />
51st Level Un-Uber Champion
